INSERT INTO messages (id, conversation_id, role, content, created_at) VALUES (186, 60, 'assistant', 'Based on the NDMO National Data Governance Interim Regulations (PoliciesEn (1).pdf), here is the data classification for the shipment fields. Classification is determined by assessing the potential impact of unauthorized disclosure on national interest, organizations, individuals, and the environment — as defined in Section 4.3 of the reference document.

| Field Name | Classification Level | Classification Rationale | Data Owner | Sensitivity Category |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| shipment_id | Restricted | Internal system identifier used to track shipments; disclosure could enable unauthorized tracking or manipulation of customs records. Internal use only. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Operational / Internal |
| shipment_ref_no | Restricted | Business reference number linking to commercial transactions; exposure could facilitate fraud or unauthorized access to shipment details. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Operational / Internal |
| shipment_type | Public | General categorization (import/export/transit) with no material harm if disclosed. Supports trade transparency. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Operational |
| shipment_date | Restricted | Transaction date that, combined with other fields, could enable reconstruction of trade patterns or facilitate targeted fraud. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Operational / Internal |
| shipment_status | Restricted | Operational status (e.g., cleared, held, in-transit); disclosure could be exploited to circumvent customs enforcement actions. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Operational / Internal |
| origin_country_code | Public | Country of origin is a standard trade data element published in aggregated customs statistics; no individual harm from disclosure. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Trade Statistics |
| destination_country_code | Public | Country of destination is standard trade data; individually benign and published in national trade reports. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Trade Statistics |
| port_of_loading | Public | Physical port information is publicly available logistics data; no harm from disclosure at field level. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Logistics |
| port_of_discharge | Public | Physical port of discharge is standard logistics information available publicly. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Logistics |
| final_destination | Confidential | Specific delivery destination of a shipment; when combined with consignee identity, could reveal business location, operational patterns, or facilitate cargo theft. Classified Confidential – Category C per NDMO framework. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Commercial / Operational |
| incoterm_code | Restricted | Commercial trade term defining risk and cost transfer; reveals contract structure between parties. Internal use. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Commercial |
| transport_mode | Public | Mode of transport (sea/air/road) is standard trade metadata with no individual harm. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Logistics |
| carrier_name | Restricted | Identifies the logistics service provider; combined with other fields could reveal commercial relationships and enable targeted interference. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Commercial / Operational |
| vessel_flight_no | Restricted | Vessel or flight number links shipment to specific transport assets; could enable cargo targeting or security exploitation. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Logistics / Security |
| bill_of_lading_no | Confidential | A legally binding shipping document number; unauthorized disclosure could enable cargo fraud, document forgery, or unauthorized release of goods. Classified Confidential – Category C. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Legal / Commercial |
| awb_no | Confidential | Air Waybill number is a key shipping document identifier; exposure risk equivalent to bill_of_lading_no — enables cargo fraud. Classified Confidential – Category C. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Legal / Commercial |
| container_no | Confidential | Unique container identifier; disclosure combined with port/vessel data could facilitate cargo theft or interference with physical assets. Classified Confidential – Category C. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Logistics / Security |
| container_type | Public | Standard container type code (e.g., 20GP, 40HC) is generic logistics metadata with no harm from disclosure. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Logistics |
| seal_no | Confidential | Customs seal number is a security control element; unauthorized disclosure could facilitate tampering with sealed containers and compromise customs enforcement. Classified Confidential – Category B. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Security / Enforcement |
| gross_weight_kg | Restricted | Shipment weight is an operational field; when combined with cargo type and route, could reveal commercially sensitive trade volumes. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Commercial / Operational |
| net_weight_kg | Restricted | Net cargo weight; same rationale as gross_weight_kg — commercially sensitive in combination with other fields. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Commercial / Operational |
| volume_cbm | Restricted | Cubic volume measure; operationally internal and commercially sensitive when linked to specific traders or cargo. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Commercial / Operational |
| total_packages | Restricted | Package count is an operational internal field; commercially sensitive in the context of trader profiling. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Operational |
| package_type | Public | Generic packaging descriptor (e.g., pallets, cartons); standard logistics metadata with no harm from disclosure. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Logistics |
| freight_currency | Restricted | Currency used in freight billing reveals financial transaction context; internal operational field. | Finance & Trade Data Owner | Financial |
| freight_amount | Confidential | Monetary value of freight charges constitutes commercial financial data; unauthorized disclosure damages competitive position of carriers and traders. Classified Confidential – Category C per NDMO Section 4.3. | Finance & Trade Data Owner | Financial / Commercial |
| insurance_amount | Confidential | Insurance value directly reflects the assessed value of cargo; disclosure causes competitive and financial harm. Classified Confidential – Category C. | Finance & Trade Data Owner | Financial / Commercial |
| created_by | Confidential | Identifies the ZATCA system user who created the record; constitutes employee/operational data and is subject to access controls under NDMO Least Privilege principle. | IT / Data Governance Owner | Personnel / Audit |
| created_at | Restricted | Audit timestamp; internal operational metadata. Disclosure in combination with user ID could enable reconstruction of system activity patterns. | IT / Data Governance Owner | Audit / Operational |
| updated_at | Restricted | Last update timestamp; internal audit trail field. Same rationale as created_at. | IT / Data Governance Owner | Audit / Operational |', '2026-03-06 06:31:28.732716');
INSERT INTO messages (id, conversation_id, role, content, created_at) VALUES (187, 60, 'user', 'how come that the classifcation level results are different than the classification level results in the interim regulation file ', '2026-03-06 06:33:32.861049');
INSERT INTO messages (id, conversation_id, role, content, created_at) VALUES (188, 60, 'assistant', 'This is a valid and important observation. Let me clarify the distinction directly.

---

**The NDMO Interim Regulations define classification levels for data assets and documents — not individual database fields.**

The four levels defined in Section 4.3 of the reference document are:

| NDMO Level | Trigger |
|---|---|
| **Top Secret** | Unauthorized disclosure causes exceptionally grave, unrecoverable damage to national interest |
| **Secret** | Unauthorized disclosure causes serious, difficult-to-recover damage |
| **Confidential** | Unauthorized disclosure causes contained damage to organizations or individuals |
| **Public** | Disclosure causes no impact |

The regulation does not define a **"Restricted"** level. That is a fifth level I introduced from general data governance practice — it was an error on my part to apply it here without flagging the deviation from the NDMO framework.

---

**What I should have done — and will now correct:**

Per the NDMO framework, the only valid classification levels are:
- **Top Secret**
- **Secret**
- **Confidential** (with sub-categories A, B, C)
- **Public**

Additionally, Section 4.4 of the reference document states:

> *"If data is not classified at the time of creation or receipt as per the classification criteria, it shall be treated as **Confidential** until correctly classified."*

---

**Here is the corrected classification table, strictly applying the NDMO framework:**

| Field Name | Classification Level | Classification Rationale | Data Owner | Sensitivity Category |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| shipment_id | Confidential – Category C | Internal system identifier; disclosure could enable unauthorized tracking of shipment records, causing damage at the level of a single entity. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Operational / Internal |
| shipment_ref_no | Confidential – Category C | Business reference number linking to commercial transactions; exposure could facilitate fraud at single-entity level. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Operational / Internal |
| shipment_type | Public | General import/export categorization; disclosure causes no impact on national interest, organizations, or individuals. | Customs & Trade Data Owner | Operational |
